  language: eng
  text: |-
    I humbly received the edict transmitted through the Wu-Yue envoy Ban, the Minister of State, and likewise your lengthy missive with detailed accounts. I consider that the resplendent carriage brought forth the imperial decree, and the fine words upon silk carried counsel and instruction. Though I received the royal proclamation with reverence and mounting gratitude, upon opening your letter my doubts have not entirely dispersed. Now I entrust to this returning messenger the candor of my heart.

    I am sustained above by Heaven's grace and pressed below by the people's support, having undeservedly inherited the marshal's authority and gained the opportunity to guide the realm. Of late, the Three Lands faced calamity, the Nine Provinces endured famine—countless folk fell prey to brigandry, and the fields lay bare and barren. Hoping to cease the tumult of war and rescue our nation from catastrophe, we established neighborly bonds in friendship. And indeed, thousands of li prospered in agriculture, and for seven or eight years the soldiers rested in peace.

    Yet in the tenth month of the year of the Rooster, suddenly conflict arose between us. At first you advanced lightly against the enemy, like the mantis raising its arms against the chariot wheel, but ultimately perceiving the difficulty, you withdrew bravely, as the mosquito bears the mountain. With clasped hands you spoke your oath, pointing to Heaven: "From this day forward, may we know eternal harmony. Should either break faith, may the gods strike us down." I too revere the martial virtue of ceasing war and cherish the humane path of sparing the sword. Thus I lifted the siege to grant rest to my weary soldiers, willingly offering hostages not for ransom but solely for the people's peace. Surely this was a great kindness to the southern people.

    Yet the blood of our covenant had scarcely dried when violence flared anew. Like the wasp's venom poisoning all life, like the wolf and tiger rampaging through the capital, our golden walls grew tight with dread and the imperial carriage trembled in alarm. Who among the lords could match the righteous dominion of Duke Huan or Lord Wen of the Spring and Autumn age? Yet you, seizing opportunity like Wang Mang and Dong Zhuo of old, have perpetrated unprecedented treachery.

    You have forced our sovereign—whose dignity stands supreme—to bow as your subject, overturning the proper order of heaven and earth. Those who might have steadied the throne through loyal counsel now labor in vain. You have slaughtered the king, burned the palace, pickled the ministers, slaughtered the people, seized the royal consorts for your own chambers, and plundered the treasures. Your evil exceeds that of Jie and Zhou; your inhumanity surpasses the most savage beasts.

    My rage strikes the heavens themselves, my resolve cuts through the very sun. Now I raise the standard of righteous war. For two years my armies have marched: on land we move like thunder and lightning; on water we surge like tiger wrestling with dragon. Each strike finds its mark; nothing is wasted. We have pursued your generals to the sea's edge, where armor lies piled like mountains. We have taken your fortress cities, leaving corpses that blanket the fields. At Yeonsan we cut down your commanders before the assembled ranks; at Mali we executed your generals beneath our flags. When we took Imjon, hundreds of your men fell. When we broke Qingzhou, your champions lost their heads. Your strongholds crumbled at the sight of our banners; your cities surrendered with their treasures intact. Kangzhou came from the south to join us; the southern regions turned westward to come east beneath our rule.

    With such victories before us, how distant lies complete restoration? We shall wash away all grievance at the waters of Ji, as Zhang Er once did, and achieve the final triumph as the Han King accomplished at Wu River. The storms shall pass; the seas shall clear forever. Heaven aids our cause—to whom shall destiny turn?

    Moreover, the King of Wu-Yue, in his vast and magnanimous virtue, has deigned to issue imperial edict, extending his mercy to heal the wounds of this eastern land. Having received such instruction, how can we fail to comply? Should you accept the royal mandate and lay down your weapons, you shall not only meet with the benevolence of the superior power, but perhaps restore the broken line of the Eastern realm. Yet should you persist in your rebellion, no repentance shall avail you then.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'The Yellow Turban Rebellion: A reference to the uprising in late Han times when Zhang Jue led rebellious forces wearing yellow headwear, becoming a metaphor in later literature for any popular uprising or civil disorder.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'The mantis: A classical allusion comparing one who foolishly resists a superior force to a mantis raising its forelegs against a chariot wheel.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'True martial virtue lies in ceasing warfare: The character for ''martial'' (武) is composed of ''to stop'' (止) and ''spear'' (戈), thus signifying the termination of armed conflict.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Duke Huan of Qi and Lord Wen of Jin: Exemplars of virtuous dominion during the Spring and Autumn period, who maintained the Zhou king''s authority while bringing order to the realm, in contrast to usurpers like Wang Mang and Dong Zhuo.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Zhang Er: A historical figure from the Warring States period who, betrayed by former allies, found refuge with Liu Bang (founder of Han) and exacted vengeance at the waters of Ji.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Wu River (Wujiang): The location where the rebel general Xiang Yu met his doom, serving as a metaphor for final triumph over rebellion.'
